The poet alludes to Xerxes king of Persia, of whom Herodotus nai-rates that he walked over the sea,

“ and sailed on dry land : alluding to his having thrown

an immense bridge over the Hellespont, and dug a channel nearly around the whole of mount Athos, through which a considerable portion of his fleet passed. There is an idle tale related of him by the same historiari, that, upon the destruction of his bridge, by a violent tempest‚ he ordered three hun- dred lashes to be inflicted on the waves, and that they should be instantly bound with chains. The courtiers of Xerxes, it should seem, had flattered him to more purpose respecting his power over this clement, than those of Canute were able to accom- plish in‘later times.
